answers.body_markdown:
When you have an `fx:controller` attribute in the root element of the FXML file, then you must not instantiate the controller class yourself (possibly unless you&#39;re also defining a custom [controller factory][1]). The `FXMLLoader` will instantiate the controller for you (via reflection by default) and it&#39;s only that instance which will have any `@FXML`-annotated fields injected. You can get this controller instance by calling [`FXMLLoader#getController()`][2] _after_ the call to `load()`.

For example, let&#39;s say you have the following FXML file and associated controller class.

**Main.fxml**:

```xml
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;

&lt;?import javafx.scene.control.Label?&gt;
&lt;?import javafx.scene.layout.StackPane?&gt;

&lt;StackPane xmlns=&quot;http://javafx.com/javafx&quot; xmlns:fx=&quot;http://javafx.com/fxml&quot;
           fx:controller=&quot;com.example.Controller&quot;&gt;
    &lt;Label fx:id=&quot;label&quot;/&gt;
&lt;/StackPane&gt;
```

**Controller.java**:

```java
package com.example;

import javafx.fxml.FXML;
import javafx.scene.control.Label;

public class Controller {

    @FXML private Label label;

    public void setLabelText(String labelText) {
        label.setText(labelText);
    }
}
```

Then you&#39;d load the FXML file, get the controller instance, and call `setLabelText` like so.

**Main.java**:

```java
package com.example;

import javafx.application.Application;
import javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader;
import javafx.scene.Parent;
import javafx.scene.Scene;
import javafx.stage.Stage;

public class Main extends Application {

    @Override
    public void start(Stage primaryStage) throws Exception {
        // Assumes &#39;Main.fxml&#39; is at the root of the class-path/module-path
        FXMLLoader loader = new FXMLLoader(Main.class.getResource(&quot;/Main.fxml&quot;));
        
        Parent root = loader.load();

        // Get *managed* controller instance (after call to &#39;load()&#39;)
        Controller controller = loader.getController();
        // Call method on the managed controller instance
        controller.setLabelText(&quot;Hello, World!&quot;);

        primaryStage.setScene(new Scene(root, 500, 300));
        primaryStage.show();
    }
}
```

If the following was done instead (similar to your code):

```java
Controller controller = new Controller();
controller.setLabelText(&quot;Hello, World!&quot;);
```

Then a `NullPointerException` would&#39;ve been thrown, because the controller instance is an _unmanaged_ instance and thus the `label` field was never injected.






















  [1]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.fxml/javafx/fxml/FXMLLoader.html#setControllerFactory(javafx.util.Callback)
  [2]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/20/javafx.fxml/javafx/fxml/FXMLLoader.html#getController()

